  "text": "Memory pressure eviction in Kubernetes is managed by the kubelet's eviction manager. Here are the key findings:\n\n**Threshold Definition (Memory Pressure):**\n\n1. **pkg/kubelet/eviction/api/types.go**: Defines SignalMemoryAvailable as 'memory.available' which represents memory capacity minus working set memory. This signal triggers eviction when available memory falls below the threshold. The threshold is defined as a Threshold struct containing the signal, operator, value, grace period, and minimum reclaim settings.\n\n2. **Default Thresholds by Platform:**\n   - **pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_linux.go**: Sets default hard eviction threshold for 'memory.available' to 100Mi\n   - **pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_others.go**: Also uses 100Mi for 'memory.available'\n   - **pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_windows.go**: Sets 500Mi for 'memory.available' (higher due to Windows overhead)\n\n**Eviction Decision Logic:**\n\n1. **pkg/kubelet/eviction/eviction_manager.go**: \n   - **NewManager()**: Creates and initializes the eviction manager with configuration\n   - **Start()**: Begins the monitoring control loop, handling kernel memory cgroup notifications for SignalMemoryAvailable and SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable thresholds\n   - **synchronize()**: Main control loop that enforces eviction thresholds. It:\n     - Gets memory stats from the summary provider\n     - Calls thresholdsMet() to check if thresholds are crossed\n     - Tracks grace periods for soft thresholds\n     - Identifies node conditions (e.g., NodeMemoryPressure) when thresholds are met\n     - Ranks pods for eviction using rankMemoryPressure()\n     - Evicts pods with immediate grace period on hard thresholds or graceful shutdown on soft thresholds\n   - **IsUnderMemoryPressure()**: Returns true if node has NodeMemoryPressure condition\n   - **Admit()**: Rejects new best-effort pods during memory pressure unless they tolerate the memory pressure taint\n\n2. **pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers.go**:\n   - **thresholdsMet()**: Core evaluation function that compares current memory.available observations against configured thresholds using the 'LessThan' operator. Returns the set of thresholds that have been crossed.\n   - **rankMemoryPressure()**: Ranks pods for eviction in order of: (1) whether pod memory usage exceeds its requests, (2) priority, (3) memory usage above requests. Pods exceeding their memory requests are evicted first.\n   - **buildSignalToRankFunc()**: Maps SignalMemoryAvailable and SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable to rankMemoryPressure ranking function\n   - **nodeConditions()**: Maps SignalMemoryAvailable to v1.NodeMemoryPressure node condition\n   - **ParseThresholdConfig()**: Parses memory.available thresholds from kubelet configuration\n\n3. **pkg/kubelet/eviction/types.go**: \n   - **Config struct**: Contains the parsed Thresholds list for memory monitoring\n   - **Manager interface**: Defines the management contract, including IsUnderMemoryPressure() method\n\n4. **pkg/kubelet/eviction/memory_threshold_notifier.go**: \n   - Integrates with kernel memcg notifications to efficiently detect when memory thresholds are crossed\n   - Triggers synchronize() immediately rather than waiting for polling interval when memory pressure detected\n\n**Pod Eviction Reason:**\nWhen memory pressure eviction occurs, pods are evicted with reason 'Evicted' and the message 'The node was low on resource: memory' (or similar). The eviction is tracked in metrics by the SignalMemoryAvailable signal."
}

